#intro

I have created a development workflow for processing SVG jigsaw puzzle outlines and input images that are cut into pieces according to the lines defined in the SVG.   I am using a wrapper script create_puzzle_pack.py to call out to the other scripts and package the results in an internal format I call 'puzzle pack format'.

# Your mission:
I have a script called 'jigsaw_piece_extractor.py' that generally works really well, however on reassembling the puzzle and comparing the pieces with the original SVG outline file I noticed there was a discrepancy in the shape of the pieces that were cut out and converted to individual PNG files.    In particular, the bezier curves defined in the SVG file have a very fluid appearance, but the cut PNG files are much simpler shapes that are a mere hint of the fluidity of their SVG definition.   I weant to fix jigsaw_piece_extractor.py so that it more accurately cuts the pixels along the bexier curves defined in the SVG input. 

# Additional information

### Puzzle pack format:
Each puzzle pack is delivered as a zip archive. After extraction, the folder structure is as follows:

puzzle_pack_name/
├── manifest.json                      # JSON file describing metadata for the pack
├── puzzle_01/
│   ├── preview.jpg                    # Preview image of the completed puzzle
│   └── layouts/
│       ├── 2x2/
│       │   ├── outline.svg
│       │   └── pieces/
│       │       ├── 0_0.png
│       │       ├── 0_1.png
│       │       ├── 1_0.png
│       │       └── 1_1.png
│       ├── 16x16/
│       │   ├── outline.svg
│       │   └── pieces/
│       │       └── 0_0.png through 15_15.png
│       └── 32x32/
│           └── (same format)
├── puzzle_02/
│   └── (same structure)

Each layout contains:
- `outline.svg`: the vector outline of the jigsaw cut pattern
- `preview-outline.png`: the preview with the cut outline for reference
- `pieces/`: transparent PNG files, each representing a jigsaw piece
- `pieces/solution.json`: JSON coordinates of all piece offsets in the 'solved' puzzle.

The puzzle pieces are named using the pattern `X_Y.png` based on their row and column in the grid (0-indexed). For example, `2_3.png` is the piece at row 2, column 3. This naming allows a script to reconstruct the solved puzzle layout using the filenames and the solution.json which then maps the X_Y grid coordinate to pixel offsets within the original puzzle image.

